The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 Mumbai, July 7: The Company Law Board has given Mahindra Satyam (erstwhile Satyam Computers) time till September 30 to publish various mandatory documents. The board has permitted extension of time up to September 30, 2010, for publication of financial results for the years ended March 31, 2009 and March 31, 2010, Mahindra Satyam said.                            
	 New Delhi, July 7: Manufacturing growth in the emerging markets has slowed sharply during the April-June quarter, from a record pace set in the first quarter, although industrial activity gathered pace in India and Russia, HSBC said today. With developed nations showing a few signs of domestic demand and are about to enter a period of fiscal retrenchment, world trade is likely to soften further.                             
	 New Delhi, July 7: The government today allotted broadband wireless spectrum to four operators. According to senior officials in the department of telecom, 20Mhz of spectrum has been given to the four firms  Infotel, Bharti, Aircel and Tikona Digital  which have licences to offer services.                             
	 New Delhi, July 7: NMDC is in talks to buy coking coal mines from Kolmar in Russia to feed its proposed steel plants in Chhattisgarh and Karnataka. When contacted, NMDC chairman Rana Som confirmed that talks were on.                            
	 Johannesburg, July 7: A fault in an undersea cable has hit Internet services between Mumbai and Mombasa since Monday and a full repair will take at least 6-8 days, Mauritius-based Seacom, which owns the cable, said today.                            
	 Mumbai, July 7: Tata Tea has been renamed Tata Global Beverages Ltd. The name change of the Tata Group company is effective from July 2.                             
	 New Delhi, July 7: HCL Technologies founder director and chief operating officer S. Raman passed away today at the age of 69.
                                                                                                                          
